eanography, 16, pp. 155-163. , doi: 10.1029/2000PA000541; Speijer, R.P., Wagner, T., Sea-level changes and black shales associated with the late Paleocene Thermal Maximum (LPTM): Organic-geochemical and micropaleontologic evidence from the southern Tethyan margin (Egypt-Israel) (2002) Catastrophic Events and Mass Extinctions: Impacts and Beyond, pp. 533-549. , Koeberl, C., and MacLeod, K.G., eds., Geological Society of America Special Paper 356; Stoll, H.M., Bains, S., Sr/Ca records of productivity during the PETM of the Weddell Sea (2003) Paleoceanography, 18. , PA1049, doi: 10.1029/2002PA000875; Thierstein, H.R., Late Cretaceous nannoplankton and the change at the Cretaceous-Tertiary boundary (1981) The Deep Sea Drilling Project: A Decade of Progress, pp. 355-394. , Warne, J.E., et al., eds., Society of Economic Paleontologists and Mineralogists Special Publication 21; Thomas, E., Extinction and food at the seafloor: A high-resolution benthic foraminiferal record across the Initial Eocene Thermal Maximum, Southern Ocean Site 690 (2003), pp. 319-332. , Geological Society of America Special Paper 369Thomas, E., Shackleton, N.J., The Paleocene-Eocene benthic foraminiferal extinction and stable isotope anomalies (1996) Correlation of the Early Paleogene in Northwest Europe, pp. 401-441. , Knox, R.W.O'B., et al., eds., Geological Society [London] Special Publication 101; Thomas, D.J., Zachos, J.C., Bralower, T.J., Thomas, E., Bohaty, S., Warming the fuel for the fire: Evidence for the thermal dissociation of methane hydrate during the Paleocene-Eocene Thermal Maximum (2002) Geology, 30, pp. 1067-1070. , doi: 10.1130/0091-7613(2002)030<1067:WTFFTF>2.0.CO;2; Tremolada, F., Bralower, T.J., Nannofossil assemblage fluctuations during the Paleocene-Eocene Thermal Maximum at Sites 213 and 401: Paleoceanographic implications (2004) Marine Micropaleontology, 52, pp. 107-116. , doi: 10.1016/j.marmicro.2004.04.002; Tripati, A., Elderfield, H., Deep sea temperature and circulation